#: ../../../advanced/shared-memory-and-synchronization.md:1
msgid "Shared Memory and Synchronization"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/shared-memory-and-synchronization.md:3
msgid ""
"Every thread in a CUDA thread block has access to a small, fast scratch-pad "
"called **shared memory**. It sits on-chip next to the SM's execution units — "
"roughly 100× faster than global memory and roughly 10× faster than the L1 "
"cache. The catch is size: typically 48–228 KB per SM depending on "
"architecture, shared across all blocks running on that SM."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/shared-memory-and-synchronization.md:9
msgid ""
"cuda-oxide exposes shared memory through `SharedArray` and "
"`DynamicSharedArray`, both designed to feel like Rust arrays while compiling "
"to PTX address space 3. This chapter covers how to use them, when to "
"synchronize, and the tiling pattern that turns naive kernels into fast ones."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/shared-memory-and-synchronization.md:15
msgid ""
"[CUDA Programming Guide — Shared Memory](https://docs.nvidia.com/cuda/cuda-"
"programming-guide/#shared-memory) for hardware details on bank structure, "
"broadcast rules, and capacity per architecture."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/shared-memory-and-synchronization.md:22
msgid "Why shared memory matters"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/shared-memory-and-synchronization.md:24
msgid ""
"Consider the naive GEMM from the [Async MLP Pipeline](../projects/async-mlp-"
"pipeline.md) project. Each thread computes one output element by reading an "
"entire row of A and an entire column of B from global memory. For a 64×64 "
"matrix, that is 128 global loads *per thread*, and every other thread in the "
"block loads many of the same elements. The hardware dutifully fetches each "
"one from DRAM — or, if you are lucky, the L2 cache."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/shared-memory-and-synchronization.md:32
msgid ""
"Shared memory changes the economics. A thread block cooperatively loads a "
"**tile** of A and a tile of B into shared memory, synchronizes, and then "
"every thread reads from the tile. Each global load is amortized across all "
"threads that reuse the element. For a 16×16 tile, that is a 16× reduction in "
"global memory traffic."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/shared-memory-and-synchronization.md:42
msgid ""
"The tiled computation pattern. Threads cooperatively load tiles of A and B "
"from global memory into `SharedArray`s, synchronize, compute partial "
"products from the fast on-chip memory, synchronize again, and repeat for the "
"next tile along the K dimension."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/shared-memory-and-synchronization.md:50
msgid "SharedArray — static shared memory"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/shared-memory-and-synchronization.md:52
msgid ""
"`SharedArray<T, N, ALIGN>` is a fixed-size array allocated in shared memory "
"at compile time. You declare it as a `static mut` inside the kernel:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/shared-memory-and-synchronization.md:55
msgid ""
"use cuda_device::thread::Runtime2DIndex;\n"
"use cuda_device::{kernel, thread, DisjointSlice, SharedArray};\n"
"\n"
"const TILE: usize = 16;\n"
"\n"
"#[kernel]\n"
"pub fn tiled_sgemm(\n"
"    m: u32, n: u32, k: u32,\n"
"    a: &[f32], b: &[f32],\n"
"    mut c: DisjointSlice<f32, Runtime2DIndex>,\n"
") {\n"
"    static mut TILE_A: SharedArray<f32, 256> = SharedArray::UNINIT;\n"
"    static mut TILE_B: SharedArray<f32, 256> = SharedArray::UNINIT;\n"
"\n"
"    let n_sz = n as usize;\n"
"    let row = thread::index_2d_row();\n"
"    let col = thread::index_2d_col();\n"
"    let tx = thread::threadIdx_x() as usize;\n"
"    let ty = thread::threadIdx_y() as usize;\n"
"\n"
"    let mut sum = 0.0f32;\n"
"    let mut t = 0u32;\n"
"\n"
"    while t < k / TILE as u32 {\n"
"        let tile_offset = t as usize * TILE;\n"
"\n"
"        // Phase 1: cooperative load\n"
"        unsafe {\n"
"            TILE_A[ty * TILE + tx] = a[row * k as usize + tile_offset + "
"tx];\n"
"            TILE_B[ty * TILE + tx] = b[(tile_offset + ty) * n_sz + col];\n"
"        }\n"
"\n"
"        // All threads must finish loading before any thread reads\n"
"        thread::sync_threads();\n"
"\n"
"        // Phase 2: compute from shared memory\n"
"        let mut i = 0usize;\n"
"        while i < TILE {\n"
"            unsafe {\n"
"                sum += TILE_A[ty * TILE + i] * TILE_B[i * TILE + tx];\n"
"            }\n"
"            i += 1;\n"
"        }\n"
"\n"
"        // Must sync before overwriting the tile in the next iteration\n"
"        thread::sync_threads();\n"
"\n"
"        t += 1;\n"
"    }\n"
"\n"
"    // SAFETY: every thread sees the same `n_sz`.\n"
"    if let Some(c_idx) = unsafe { thread::index_2d_runtime(n_sz) } {\n"
"        if let Some(c_elem) = c.get_mut(c_idx) {\n"
"            *c_elem = sum;\n"
"        }\n"
"    }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/shared-memory-and-synchronization.md:115
msgid "Declaration rules"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/shared-memory-and-synchronization.md:117
msgid ""
"`SharedArray` must be declared as `static mut` inside the kernel function "
"body. This tells the compiler to allocate it in PTX shared address space (`."
"shared`). The `UNINIT` constant skips initialization — the contents are "
"undefined until threads write to them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/shared-memory-and-synchronization.md:38
msgid "Parameter"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/shared-memory-and-synchronization.md:38
msgid "Meaning"
msgstr ""

